1
00:00:05,541 --> 00:00:08,333
If we could hang 
upon an endless clothesline

2
00:00:08,333 --> 00:00:12,958
all the garments we’ve worn 
from birth to life’s twilight

3
00:00:12,958 --> 00:00:16,833
we would feel the rhythm 
of time’s fleeting course.

4
00:00:16,833 --> 00:00:21,666
And if we could spread upon it 
all the feats of our mothers and fathers 

5
00:00:21,666 --> 00:00:23,666
and ours as well

6
00:00:23,666 --> 00:00:26,333
we would weave lace upon wire

7
00:00:26,333 --> 00:00:29,333
swaying in the wind’s tender embrace.

8
00:00:30,458 --> 00:00:35,041
Everything begins, endures and ends

9
00:00:35,041 --> 00:00:37,083
sometimes in a roar

10
00:00:37,083 --> 00:00:40,000
sometimes unnoticed.

11
00:00:40,625 --> 00:00:44,375
Wear and tear, that quiet story
no one cares to hear

12
00:00:44,375 --> 00:00:46,333
least of all the sellers  

13
00:00:46,333 --> 00:00:48,416
spares nothing

14
00:00:48,416 --> 00:00:49,666
not even them.

15
00:00:51,458 --> 00:00:53,625
On Thursday, at rush hour

16
00:00:53,625 --> 00:00:59,291
I wonder about the car graveyards’ capacity
to store our fleeting shells.

17
00:00:59,291 --> 00:01:02,708
The rare materials
they're made of will end up

18
00:01:02,708 --> 00:01:06,000
like everything else, in the dump

19
00:01:06,000 --> 00:01:09,875
alongside our paperbacks
and encyclopedias

20
00:01:09,875 --> 00:01:15,000
our favorite shoes,
and our lifetime-guaranteed Tupperware.

21
00:01:17,791 --> 00:01:22,041
When the traces of what 
we once were are swept away

22
00:01:22,041 --> 00:01:25,000
our vanities and pretensions gone 

23
00:01:25,000 --> 00:01:28,041
what will remain of us?

24
00:01:28,041 --> 00:01:31,916
Why, after all,
should our civilization be immortal?

25
00:01:31,916 --> 00:01:34,250
And why of all species

26
00:01:34,250 --> 00:01:37,541
should ours evade 
the fate that befalls the rest?

27
00:01:38,750 --> 00:01:41,208
From where does this bold claim arise

28
00:01:41,208 --> 00:01:43,000
to live forever

29
00:01:43,000 --> 00:01:45,458
never reaching the end of what we are?

30
00:01:47,833 --> 00:01:51,958
Typhoons and fires come to raze 
what we hold dear

31
00:01:51,958 --> 00:01:56,333
what we twisted in every guise
we could conjure.

32
00:01:57,000 --> 00:02:00,333
But is it truly so grave, I wonder?

33
00:02:01,000 --> 00:02:03,291
Twenty million years from now

34
00:02:03,291 --> 00:02:06,666
when a new natural order 
has replaced our own

35
00:02:06,666 --> 00:02:09,333
what will living beings look like?

36
00:02:09,333 --> 00:02:12,333
And what will they have 
inherited from us?

37
00:02:13,166 --> 00:02:16,166
If birds are the remnants of dinosaurs

38
00:02:16,166 --> 00:02:19,333
I like to think that the creatures
of the planet's next chapter

39
00:02:20,333 --> 00:02:22,875
will have kept a part of us

40
00:02:23,791 --> 00:02:25,416
in their gestures

41
00:02:25,416 --> 00:02:27,541
their gaze

42
00:02:27,541 --> 00:02:30,500
their stride.

43
00:02:30,500 --> 00:02:33,625
Perhaps they will have freed themselves 
from our ambitions

44
00:02:33,625 --> 00:02:38,333
our pride,
and our fantasies of immortality.

45
00:02:39,708 --> 00:02:41,791
All that will remain of us then

46
00:02:41,791 --> 00:02:44,666
will be a few harmless ideas

47
00:02:44,666 --> 00:02:47,708
the intangible legacy 
of our wild loves

48
00:02:47,708 --> 00:02:49,791
and noble souls

49
00:02:49,791 --> 00:02:54,833
encapsulated in the amber 
of our vanished societies.
